{
  "texts": [
    "The PMD algorithm is conceptually simple.",
    "Starting with an arbitrary initial policy π 0 and iteration counter k = 0, PMD finds the next policy π k+1 (⋅|s) that solves the minimization problem (Equ. (6)).",
    "Then we increment k and repeat the update.",
    "Here, Q π (s, a) is called the Q-function that is defined as the expected cost when we start the system at state s ∈ S with action a ∈ A and continue running under policy π.",
    "Since the Q-function is not known in advance, it can be estimated either by Monte Carlo simulation via independent trajectories or a stochastic iterative method such as temporal difference (TD) learning 48."
  ]
}